  "local_port": 59280,
  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "Though people tell me I am pretty, why do I sometimes feel not pretty or I don't like what I see in the mirror?",
  "response": "Feeling this way is entirely normal and something many people experience, even when others compliment their appearance. Here are some possible reasons why you might feel this way:\n\n### 1. **Self-Perception vs. External Validation**\n   - **Internal Critic:** We often see ourselves through a critical lens, focusing on perceived flaws or imperfections that others might not notice. This inner critic can overshadow positive feedback from others.\n   - **Expectations:** Society and media often promote narrow beauty standards, making it easy to compare yourself to unrealistic ideals and feel like you don\u2019t measure up.\n\n### 2. **Mood and Mental State**\n   - **Self-Esteem:** Feeling unattractive can sometimes be tied to self-esteem or emotional well-being. If you\u2019re feeling down, anxious, or stressed, it can affect how you see yourself.\n   - **Mood Shifts:** Your perception of your appearance can fluctuate based on your mood. On some days, you might feel confident, while on others, you might feel less secure.\n\n### 3. **Comparison to Others**\n   - **Social Media and Comparison Culture:** Constantly comparing yourself to others, especially on social media, can make you feel like you don\u2019t meet certain beauty standards, even if those standards are unrealistic.\n   - **Selective Focus:** You might fixate on aspects of your appearance that you don\u2019t like, while ignoring the features that others admire about you.\n\n### 4. **External Influences**\n   - **Criticism:** Negative comments from others, even if rare, can leave a lasting impact and make you doubt your appearance.\n   - **Societal Pressure:** Societal standards of beauty can create feelings of inadequacy, even if you objectively meet those standards.\n\n### 5. **Shifting Self-Image**\n   - **Changing Identity:** As you grow and evolve, your self-image may shift, and it can take time to feel confident in your new identity or appearance.\n   - **Context Matters:** How you feel about your appearance can also depend on the context or situation. For example, you might feel less confident in certain environments or around specific people.\n\n### What You Can Do:\n   - **Practice Self-Compassion:** Treat yourself with kindness and remind yourself that everyone has insecurities.\n   - **Focus on What You Love:** Shift your focus to the features or qualities you do like about yourself.\n   - **Limit Comparisons:** Reduce exposure to content or environments that trigger feelings of inadequacy.\n   - **Celebrate Your Uniqueness:** Remind yourself that beauty is diverse and subjective\u2014your individuality is what makes you special.\n   - **Seek Support:** If these feelings persist and affect your well-being, talking to a trusted friend or therapist can help.\n\nRemember, beauty is multifaceted and goes far beyond physical appearance. It\u2019s okay to have days when you don\u2019t feel your best\u2014what matters most is how you treat yourself and others. \ud83d\udc9b",
  "temperature": 1.0,
